t's large and vibrant network of daily newspapers, as well as the weekly or monthly opinion journals-emphasizing the open, diverse, and pluralistic nature of the interwar political and cultural arena. In examining Muslim views of fascism at the moment when classical fascism was at its peak, this enlightening book seriously challenges the recent assumption of an inherent Muslim predisposition toward authoritarianism, totalitarianism, and "Islamo-Fascism."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aDemocracyxHistoryxEgypt. 0aDemocracyzEgyptxHistory. 0aFascismxHistoryxEgypt. 0aFascismzEgyptxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Egypt (see also Ancient / Egypt).2bisacsh1 aJankowski, James, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804772556zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804772556423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804772556.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles